12:33.920 --> 12:38.340
Brian Aldiss does unexpected but fascinating things in his science fiction stories

12:38.340 --> 12:40.180
Though Aldiss is often an innovator

12:40.180 --> 12:43.400
He also understands and cherishes the traditions of science fiction

12:43.400 --> 12:46.720
Aldiss has demonstrated his fondness for science fiction's past

12:46.720 --> 12:48.780
By redoing some of its classic novels

12:48.780 --> 12:50.820
An Island Called Moreau, for instance

12:50.820 --> 12:53.720
Was based on H.G. Wells' The Island of Dr. Moreau

12:53.720 --> 12:55.600
And his book Frankenstein Unbound

12:55.600 --> 12:57.300
Drew on Mary Shelley's Frankenstein

12:57.300 --> 12:58.540
Published in 1818

12:58.540 --> 13:00.700
Which some call the first science fiction novel

13:00.700 --> 13:05.140
Aldiss relates the impulse behind his writing of Frankenstein Unbound

13:06.140 --> 13:10.480
I think that I write about the things that fascinate me most

13:10.480 --> 13:13.820
And I'm kind of a literary man

13:13.820 --> 13:16.800
And I certainly

13:16.800 --> 13:20.720
Much admire Mary Shelley's Frankenstein

13:20.720 --> 13:22.920
It's the most remarkable work for anyone

13:22.920 --> 13:24.860
Not least for a young lady

13:24.860 --> 13:27.660
Not quite touching 18

13:28.960 --> 13:34.020
And when I had the impulse to write Frankenstein Unbound

13:34.020 --> 13:38.080
It was really an exegetical impulse

13:38.080 --> 13:42.260
To draw everybody's attention if possible

13:42.260 --> 13:45.320
To the excellence of that original novel

13:45.320 --> 13:51.280
Which as you know has been slandered and pilloried

13:51.280 --> 13:52.660
By the filmmakers

13:52.660 --> 13:54.760
Who've seen nothing better in it

13:54.760 --> 13:59.400
Than a stupid, shambling, and inarticulate monster

13:59.400 --> 14:02.180
I wanted to restore the monster

14:02.180 --> 14:05.460
To his true evil power

14:05.460 --> 14:11.800
As an articulate feeling and maimed being

14:11.800 --> 14:14.660
Worthy of our compassion

14:14.660 --> 14:17.700
And perhaps our hatred

14:19.240 --> 14:21.520
Aldiss says there was a true creative impulse

14:21.520 --> 14:22.960
Behind Frankenstein Unbound

14:22.960 --> 14:25.340
But that wasn't so for an island called Moreau

14:26.240 --> 14:28.460
I have to admit that later on

14:28.460 --> 14:30.100
I did the same thing with Wells'

14:30.420 --> 14:32.200
Island of Dr. Moreau

14:34.460 --> 14:36.200
And that was

14:36.200 --> 14:37.640
I believe

14:37.640 --> 14:38.600
Ill-advised

14:38.600 --> 14:41.360
It's one of the few novels I've written

14:41.360 --> 14:42.660
That didn't begin with

14:42.660 --> 14:45.200
Some kind of genuine

14:48.700 --> 14:50.040
Lust to create

14:50.040 --> 14:51.520
Will to create

14:53.480 --> 14:55.440
With fire in my stomach

14:56.580 --> 14:58.700
I just thought it was something I could do

14:58.700 --> 15:00.580
And that was too tiny a motive

15:00.580 --> 15:01.100
I believe

15:01.100 --> 15:03.020
For the book that I eventually turned out

15:03.700 --> 15:05.520
I don't believe that it

15:06.880 --> 15:07.440
Supersedes

15:07.440 --> 15:08.460
Or in any way

15:09.260 --> 15:09.820
Aids

15:09.820 --> 15:10.880
The Wells

15:10.880 --> 15:11.900
Version

15:11.900 --> 15:13.860
The funny thing is

15:13.860 --> 15:15.160
I have to say

15:15.160 --> 15:18.200
That that novel was extremely well received

15:18.200 --> 15:19.580
In this country

15:19.580 --> 15:20.840
And in Great Britain

15:21.940 --> 15:24.360
Another Aldiss tribute to science fiction's past

15:24.360 --> 15:25.180
Is his novella

15:25.180 --> 15:26.000
The Saliva Tree

15:26.000 --> 15:27.260
It's a playful book

15:27.260 --> 15:28.980
A clever tribute to H.G. Wells

15:28.980 --> 15:31.160
Who happens to be an unseen character in it

15:31.160 --> 15:33.340
It's about an invisible alien monster

15:33.340 --> 15:35.680
Ravaging the countryside of late Victorian England

15:35.680 --> 15:38.000
Invading monsters and invisibility

15:38.000 --> 15:39.640
Are two of Wells' themes of course

15:39.640 --> 15:40.660
And during the story

15:40.660 --> 15:41.620
All of Wells' themes

15:41.620 --> 15:42.880
And the titles of his books

15:42.880 --> 15:44.200
Are somehow worked in

15:44.200 --> 15:45.940
The story's main character

15:45.940 --> 15:46.860
Gregory Rolles

15:46.860 --> 15:48.460
Has been writing letters to H.G. Wells

15:48.460 --> 15:49.920
About the happenings in the countryside

15:50.460 --> 15:51.900
Wells comes to meet Rolles

15:51.900 --> 15:52.780
As the story ends

15:53.740 --> 15:55.280
Our central character

15:55.280 --> 15:56.120
Is about

15:56.120 --> 15:58.360
To relate to H.G. Wells

15:58.360 --> 16:01.040
The horrific events

16:01.040 --> 16:01.960
That have gone on

16:01.960 --> 16:03.720
Down on the farm

16:04.920 --> 16:07.200
And in those events

16:07.200 --> 16:08.580
Are really

16:09.960 --> 16:11.320
The germs

16:11.320 --> 16:12.880
For all of

16:12.880 --> 16:14.500
Wells' science fiction

16:15.440 --> 16:16.420
I mean

16:16.420 --> 16:17.540
You know

16:17.540 --> 16:18.000
There's

16:19.080 --> 16:20.640
There's a kind of a

16:20.640 --> 16:22.460
A joke on H.G. Wells there

16:22.460 --> 16:23.060
I mean

16:23.060 --> 16:24.860
We all owe a great debt

16:24.860 --> 16:25.780
To H.G. Wells

16:25.780 --> 16:26.140
Because

16:26.140 --> 16:27.780
He preempted

16:27.780 --> 16:29.020
Almost all of the

16:29.020 --> 16:30.200
Science fiction themes

16:31.040 --> 16:32.200
And so in a way

16:32.200 --> 16:33.380
The saliva tree

16:33.380 --> 16:34.140
Is a kind of

16:34.140 --> 16:35.340
Horrific joke

16:35.340 --> 16:37.060
To show that in fact

16:37.060 --> 16:38.280
Wells didn't have

16:38.280 --> 16:39.480
Any original ideas

16:39.480 --> 16:40.220
They were all

16:40.220 --> 16:41.080
Given to him

16:41.080 --> 16:41.880
By this guy

16:41.880 --> 16:43.380
Who knocks on the door

